This article describes a tool designed to transform normal URLs into suspicious-looking ones that appear malicious. The tool functions as a redirect service (similar to TinyURL) but instead of shortening links, it deliberately makes them look dangerous. Users can select different themes (like crypto, phishing, gambling) and length options to customize how suspicious the generated URL appears, though the resulting link simply redirects to the original destination without any actual malicious behavior.

## Key Insight
The most interesting takeaway is the tool's purpose as a social engineering demonstration - it highlights how easily legitimate web traffic can be disguised to look threatening, which serves as an educational tool about phishing techniques while explicitly acknowledging its potential to "piss off" IT security teams. The article details iTerm2's built-in web browser functionality, which integrates browsing capabilities alongside terminal sessions in the same window/tab/split pane hierarchy. It explains how to enable the browser, its core features (navigation, text selection, privacy options), and advanced capabilities like named marks, instant replay, and AI integration. The browser maintains iTerm2's familiar keyboard shortcuts and functionality while adding web-specific features.
